Ask HN: How do we protect news from deepfakes?
text:
Are any startups working on combatting deepfakes and their soon-to-be massive impact in information warfare? Any ideas on how an average person can verify a news clipping on TikTok is by a genuine anchor or actually a deepfake?

Assuming deepfakes and deepfake-spotters one-up each other are there other methods we can use to prove a video (clipping?) came from an authentic source?

Ask HN: Why don't real estate tech sites have better filter options?
text:
Currently in a house hunt after many years planning and preparing, and I'm getting frustrated with the many publicly available clones of realtor / zillow. There seems to be no good way to filter by things like price per square foot, crime rates, nearby green space, school quality, and so forth.

Is there anything out there that actually allows for real filtering beyond simple things like age of home, number of bedrooms and the like?

title: Ask HN: How can Netflix and Amazon Prime be this bad at recommending content?
text:
I’ve literally spent 20 minutes for the xth time in a row looking for anything that remotely captures me on both platforms and in the end did not watch anything. I’ve spent hundreds of hours binging series and movies on both platforms, but neither seems able to use this to suggest anything I like. I’ll probably cancel at least Netflix.

It would be so easy: - Store series I‘ve watched, show me new seasons when they release. - neither does it reliably. - Don’t keep suggesting things I have watched, except in a „watch again“ category. Especially using new pictures, getting me to click on the same stuff only to realize that I have seen this already.

Given the billions invested in these UIs, how can they fail so miserably? What am I missing? This makes no economic sense … or am I just a weird edge case, and this kind of UI works for the majority?
